Incorporating all requested functionalities into a Province class using C++ and raylib, here's a guideline on how to create such a class. Note, due to complexity and broadness of the question, some simplifications are made, and assumptions are stated, where necessary. This guide assumes you have basic knowledge of raylib and C++.

### Header file: Province.hpp

```cpp
#ifndef PROVINCE_HPP
#define PROVINCE_HPP

#include "raylib.h"
#include <vector>
#include <string>

class Province {
public:
    Province();
    ~Province();

    void drawProvince(Color fillColor, float strokeThickness, int strokeType);
    void drawPoints();
    void deletePoints();
    void savePointsToFile(std::string filename);
    bool deleteProvince(Vector2 mousePoint);
    void loadProvincesFromFile(std::string filename);

private:
    struct Point {
        int x, y;
    };

    std::vector<Point> points; // Points of the province being drawn or manipulated
    std::vector<std::vector<Point>> provinces; // List of provinces loaded from file

    void parseLineToPoints(const std::string& lineX, const std::string& lineY);
